    id: 2, emoji: "🦶",
    title: "AFO (Ankle Foot Orthosis) for Foot Drop: Everything You Need to Know",
    category: "Orthotics", ageGroup: "Adults",
    date: "March 2026", readTime: "6 min read",
    excerpt: "Foot drop is a condition in which lifting the front of the foot becomes difficult. An AFO (Ankle Foot Orthosis) is the most effective non-surgical treatment. Here is how it works.",
    content: `Foot drop — the inability to lift the front part of the foot during walking — affects millions of people in India. It is commonly caused by stroke, spinal cord injury, multiple sclerosis, or common peroneal nerve palsy. Without treatment, it causes a dangerous shuffling gait that significantly increases the risk of falls.

## What Is an AFO?

An Ankle Foot Orthosis (AFO) is a brace that supports the ankle and foot, preventing the toe from dragging on the ground during the swing phase of walking. It is worn inside the shoe, running along the back of the calf and under the foot.

## Types of AFOs

**Solid (Rigid) AFO**
- Maximum support and control
- Ideal for severe foot drop or significant spasticity
- Made from polypropylene — lightweight yet durable
- Custom-moulded to your exact leg shape

**Posterior Leaf Spring (PLS) AFO**
- Flexible design that stores and releases energy
- Best for mild-to-moderate foot drop with good ankle stability
- Produces a more natural gait pattern
- The most commonly prescribed type at ${CLINIC}

**Articulated AFO**
- Has a hinge at the ankle joint
- Allows controlled plantar and dorsiflexion movement
- Best for patients who retain partial ankle movement

**Hinged AFO with Dorsiflexion Assist**
- A spring mechanism assists in lifting the foot
- Closest to natural walking movement
- A premium option for active patients

## Who Needs an AFO?

- Stroke survivors with foot drop
- Spinal cord injury patients
- Children and adults with cerebral palsy
- Peroneal nerve palsy (common in rural UP, associated with prolonged squatting positions)
- Post-surgical foot drop
- Patients with multiple sclerosis

## The Custom vs. Prefabricated Debate

Many patients purchase prefabricated (off-the-shelf) AFOs from medical stores. These are cheaper, but they do not fit the exact shape of your leg, cannot be adjusted for your specific gait pattern, and often cause pressure sores and inconsistent support.

A custom-moulded AFO from ${CLINIC} takes 5–7 days and costs ₹3,000–₹6,000. It lasts 3–5 years and prevents secondary joint problems caused by poorly fitting braces.

## Conclusion

Foot drop need not define your life. A properly prescribed and fitted AFO — whether a solid, leaf spring, or articulated type — can restore safe, confident walking. Book a free assessment at ${CLINIC} to discuss your options.`
