    date: "February 2026", readTime: "7 min read",
    excerpt: "Diabetes is the leading cause of lower limb amputation in India. The right footwear — and a disciplined foot care routine — can prevent ulcers, infections, and ultimately save your limb.",
    content: `India has over 80 million people living with diabetes — one of the highest figures in the world. Of these, approximately 15% will develop a diabetic foot ulcer during their lifetime. Without proper management, these ulcers lead to infection, gangrene, and amputation.

The tragedy is that up to 85% of diabetes-related amputations are preventable with proper foot care and appropriate footwear.

## Why Diabetic Feet Require Special Attention

Diabetes causes two key problems that make the feet particularly vulnerable:

**Peripheral Neuropathy** — Nerve damage means you cannot feel pain, heat, or pressure normally. A small stone in your shoe, a blister from tight footwear, or a minor cut can go unnoticed for days — and become infected before you are even aware of it.

**Peripheral Vascular Disease** — Reduced blood flow means wounds heal slowly or not at all. Even minor injuries can become chronic, non-healing ulcers.

## MCR Chappals — India's Most Important Diabetic Footwear

Micro Cellular Rubber (MCR) footwear is the standard recommendation in Indian diabetes guidelines. The soft, porous rubber reduces peak plantar pressure by up to 30%, is washable and hygienic, and costs just ₹800–₹2,000. It is suitable for both indoor and light outdoor use.

MCR footwear is available at ${CLINIC} in multiple sizes and widths.

## Custom Insoles for Diabetic Patients

For patients with existing deformities such as hammer toes, Charcot foot, or prominent metatarsal heads, custom orthotic insoles are essential. Made from EVA foam and PPT material, they off-load pressure from at-risk areas with precision.

Cost: ₹1,200–₹3,000 for a pair of custom insoles — a small investment compared to the cost of managing a diabetic foot ulcer.

## Daily Foot Care Routine for Patients with Diabetes

1. Inspect both feet daily — use a mirror for the sole of the foot
2. Wash feet in lukewarm water (test the temperature with your elbow, not your feet)
3. Dry carefully between the toes
4. Moisturise daily, but NOT between the toes
5. Never walk barefoot, even at home
6. Always check inside your shoes before wearing them
7. Cut toenails straight across — never rounded at the corners
8. Seek professional advice at any sign of redness, swelling, or wounds

Do not ignore any foot problem if you have diabetes. Early intervention saves limbs.`
